            The error message "Exception in thread "main" java.lang.NullPointerException: Cannot invoke "SavingsAccount.printAccountInfo()" because "accounts[i]" is null" indicates that the variable `accounts` is an array of SavingsAccount objects, and one of its elements is null.

The code snippet you provided shows that the error occurs in the `printBankSummary()` method of the `Bank` class. This method calls the `printAccountInfo()` method on each element of the `accounts` array using a for loop. However, at least one of the elements in this array is null, which causes the NPE when you try to call a method on it.

To fix this error, you need to find out why one of the elements in the `accounts` array is null and prevent that from happening. Here are some possible solutions:

1. Check if the element is null before calling its methods: You can add an extra check inside the for loop to see if the current element is null, and skip it if it is. For example:
```java
for (int i = 0; i < accounts.length; i++) {
    SavingsAccount account = accounts[i];
    if (account != null) {
        account.printAccountInfo();
    } else {
        System.out.println("Skipping null account");
    }
}
```
1. Initialize the array with default values: You can initialize each element of the `accounts` array with a default value when it is created, such as an empty SavingsAccount object. For example:
```java
SavingsAccount[] accounts = new SavingsAccount[5];
for (int i = 0; i < accounts.length; i++) {
    accounts[i] = new SavingsAccount();
}
```
1. Use a collection instead of an array: Instead of using an array, you can use a collection such as a `List` or a `Set` to store the SavingsAccount objects. This will allow you to add and remove elements dynamically, without worrying about null pointers. For example:
```java
List<SavingsAccount> accounts = new ArrayList<>();
accounts.add(new SavingsAccount());
// ...
for (SavingsAccount account : accounts) {
    account.printAccountInfo();
}
```
